Infrastructure Description:
Components:
Server 1: Load Balancer (HAproxy Cluster)

Purpose: Load balancer distributes incoming traffic across multiple servers for improved performance, scalability, and reliability.
Cluster Configuration: HAproxy configured as a cluster with redundancy to ensure high availability and fault tolerance.
Server 2: Web Server

Purpose: Specifically handles HTTP requests from clients (browsers) and serves static content like HTML, CSS, and images.
Role: Focuses on efficiently delivering content to users, optimizing web page loading, and managing client-server interactions.
Server 3: Application Server

Purpose: Executes dynamic code, handles application logic, and interacts with databases or other resources as needed.
Role: Processes business logic, executes scripts, and generates dynamic content based on user requests.
Server 4: Database Server

Purpose: Stores and manages structured data, allowing the application server to retrieve, modify, or store information.
Role: Handles data storage, retrieval, and management, ensuring data integrity and availability for the application.
Specifics Explained:
Load Balancer:
Why Add It: Load balancers evenly distribute incoming traffic among multiple servers, enhancing performance by preventing overload on any single server. A cluster setup with HAproxy ensures fault tolerance and continuous availability.
Web Server vs. Application Server:
Web Server: Dedicated to serving static content and handling HTTP requests. This separation allows optimized delivery of web resources and efficient handling of client interactions.
Application Server: Focused on executing dynamic code, processing logic, and interacting with databases or other backend services. This division enables specialized handling of application-specific functionalities.
Why Split Components into Separate Servers:
Scalability and Performance: Separating components allows each server to specialize in its role, optimizing resource utilization and scalability. It prevents contention for resources and enables easy scaling of individual components based on demand.
This setup ensures a structured and specialized handling of different tasks within the infrastructure, promoting efficient resource allocation and streamlined performance for the application.

